{"id":"1510.05273","submitter":"Ehud Eilon","authors":"Ehud Eilon and Amos Ori","title":"Adaptive gauge method for long-time double-null simulations of spherical\n  black-hole spacetimes","comments":"38 pages, 18 figures. Added References","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. D 93, 024016 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevD.93.024016","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Double-null coordinates are highly useful in numerical simulations of\ndynamical spherically-symmetric black holes (BHs). However, they become\nproblematic in long-time simulations: Along the event horizon, the truncation\nerror grows exponentially in the outgoing Eddington null coordinate - which we\ndenote $v_e$ - and runs out of control for a sufficiently long interval of\n$v_e$. This problem, if not properly addressed, would destroy the numerics both\ninside and outside the black hole at late times (i.e. large $v_e$). In this\npaper we explore the origin of this problem, and propose a resolution based on\nadaptive gauge for the ingoing null coordinate $u$. This resolves the problem\noutside the BH - and also inside the BH, if the latter is uncharged. However,\nin the case of a charged BH, an analogous large-$v_e$ numerical problem occurs\nat the inner horizon. We thus generalize our adaptive-gauge method in order to\novercome the IH problem as well. This improved adaptive gauge, to which we\nrefer as the maximal-$\\sigma$ gauge, allows long-$v$ double-null numerical\nsimulation across both the event horizon and the (outgoing) inner horizon, and\nup to the vicinity of the spacelike $r=0$ singularity. We conclude by\npresenting a few numerical results deep inside a perturbed charged BH, in the\nvicinity of the contracting Cauchy Horizon.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 18 Oct 2015 16:20:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Oct 2015 12:26:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-20"}
